The paper discusses emotionally annotated databases, which are primarily used in research of human emotions and development of stress-related mental disorders. This suggests that the paper may belong to the Human-Computer Interaction (cs.HC) sub-category. The paper also mentions the use of multimedia documents, which suggests that it may belong to the Multimedia (cs.MM) sub-category. Additionally, the paper discusses the tagging of affective content, which suggests that it may belong to the Natural Language Processing (cs.CL) sub-category. The paper also mentions the use of information refinement processes, which suggests that it may belong to the Information Retrieval (cs.IR) sub-category. Finally, the paper mentions the use of multimedia documents with maximum personal ego relevance, which suggests that it may belong to the Computer Vision (cs.CV) sub-category.
